The error is coming from ModelMapper, not from Spring Boot or JPA.

Why this happens
ModelMapper is trying to map your EmployeeRequestDto to your Employee entity.

The exception says:

Employee.setEmployee_id()

matches multiple source property hierarchies

EmployeeRequestDto.getDepartment_id()
EmployeeRequestDto.getManager_id()
This means ModelMapper is confused because of your field names.

It is trying to map

employee_id
from

department_id
manager_id
because they all end with _id.

Example
Suppose your DTO is

public class EmployeeRequestDto {

    private Long department_id;
    private Long manager_id;
}
and your entity is

@Entity
public class Employee {

    private Long employee_id;

    @ManyToOne
    private Department department;

    @ManyToOne
    private Employee manager;
}
ModelMapper tokenizes the names like

employee_id  -> employee + id
department_id -> department + id
manager_id -> manager + id
Since all have an id, it cannot determine which one should populate employee_id.

Solution 1 (Recommended)
Do not use ModelMapper for entities having relationships.

Instead map manually.

Employee employee = new Employee();

employee.setEmployeeCode(dto.getEmployee_code());
employee.setFirstName(dto.getFirst_name());
employee.setLastName(dto.getLast_name());
Then fetch the related entities

Department department = departmentRepository.findById(dto.getDepartment_id())
        .orElseThrow(() -> new RuntimeException("Department not found"));

employee.setDepartment(department);

Employee manager = employeeRepository.findById(dto.getManager_id())
        .orElseThrow(() -> new RuntimeException("Manager not found"));

employee.setManager(manager);
This is the approach followed in most Spring Boot projects.

Solution 2
Tell ModelMapper to ignore employee_id.

modelMapper.typeMap(EmployeeRequestDto.class, Employee.class)
        .addMappings(mapper -> mapper.skip(Employee::setEmployee_id));
Solution 3
If your DTO contains

private Long employee_id;
private Long department_id;
private Long manager_id;
then explicitly map

TypeMap<EmployeeRequestDto, Employee> typeMap =
        modelMapper.createTypeMap(EmployeeRequestDto.class, Employee.class);

typeMap.addMappings(mapper -> {
    mapper.map(EmployeeRequestDto::getEmployee_id,
               Employee::setEmployee_id);

    mapper.skip(Employee::setDepartment);
    mapper.skip(Employee::setManager);
});
Then set department and manager manually.

Solution 4 (Better DTO naming)
Instead of

department_id
manager_id
employee_id
use

private Long departmentId;
private Long managerId;
private Long employeeId;
ModelMapper works much better with camelCase than snake_case.

