Description:

Parameter 0 of constructor in com.ems.employee.service.EmployeeService required a bean of type 'com.ems.employee.utils.EmployeeMapper' that could not be found.

The injection point has the following annotations:
	- @org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired(required=true)


Action:

Consider defining a bean of type 'com.ems.employee.utils.EmployeeMapper' in your configuration.

This error is a Spring Dependency Injection issue. Spring is unable to create an instance of EmployeeService because it cannot find a bean of type EmployeeMapper.

Error
Parameter 0 of constructor in EmployeeService required a bean of type
'com.ems.employee.utils.EmployeeMapper' that could not be found.
This means your service probably looks like:

@Service
public class EmployeeService {

    private final EmployeeMapper employeeMapper;

    @Autowired
    public EmployeeService(EmployeeMapper employeeMapper) {
        this.employeeMapper = employeeMapper;
    }
}
But Spring doesn't know how to create EmployeeMapper.

Solution 1 (Most Common)
If EmployeeMapper is your own class, annotate it with @Component.

@Component
public class EmployeeMapper {

    // mapping methods
}
Spring Boot automatically scans it and creates a bean.

Solution 2 (If it is an interface)
If your mapper is an interface like

public interface EmployeeMapper {
    Employee toEntity(EmployeeRequestDto dto);
}
Spring cannot instantiate an interface.

You need an implementation.

@Component
public class EmployeeMapperImpl implements EmployeeMapper {

    @Override
    public Employee toEntity(EmployeeRequestDto dto) {
        // implementation
    }
}
Solution 3 (If you're using MapStruct)
If you're using MapStruct, your mapper should be declared like this:

@Mapper(componentModel = "spring")
public interface EmployeeMapper {

    Employee toEntity(EmployeeRequestDto dto);

    EmployeeResponseDto toDto(Employee employee);
}
Then ensure you have the MapStruct dependencies and annotation processor configured in your Maven build. Spring will then discover the generated implementation automatically.

Solution 4 (If you forgot @Bean)
If you create the mapper manually, register it as a bean:

@Configuration
public class MapperConfig {

    @Bean
    public EmployeeMapper employeeMapper() {
        return new EmployeeMapper();
    }
}
